    <div class="article-body" data-pp-location="article body" >

                    <div class="promo-series | size03 out03 wrap left wide-sm | hide-print">
                <div class="promo-series__header stretched-link-contain">
                                                                    
                        <a href="https://www.propublica.org/series/uprooted" class="stretched-link">
                            <img class="promo-series__art" width="400" height="267" sizes="(min-width: 1520px) 257px, (min-width: 1260px) calc(20vw - 10px), (min-width: 960px) calc(20vw - 50px), (min-width: 780px) calc(25vw - 40px), 96px" alt="" srcset="https://img.assets-c3.propublica.org/images/series/Eminent-Domain-Series-Page-Promo.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=133&amp;q=75&amp;w=200&amp;s=f9bf95c648d35fb339d622b6ff31d487 200w, https://img.assets-c3.propublica.org/images/series/Eminent-Domain-Series-Page-Promo.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=267&amp;q=75&amp;w=400&amp;s=31b9a1d254fce0f5d12d2d8666107096 400w, https://img.assets-c3.propublica.org/images/series/Eminent-Domain-Series-Page-Promo.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=400&amp;q=75&amp;w=600&amp;s=78d9dc4fa52aa2a6767932dbd1c0b5a1 600w" loading="lazy" />
                        </a>
                                        <h3 class="promo-series__name">
                        <span class="a11y">Series: </span>
                        <span class="promo-series__title">Uprooted:</span>
                                                <span class="promo-series__tagline">Virginia Universities Have Expanded by Dislodging Black Communities</span>
                                            </h3>
                </div>
                                    <div class="promo-series__introduction | hide-below-lg">
                        <p>In the second half of the 20th century, the establishment and expansion of public universities across Virginia uprooted Black families, hindering their efforts to accumulate wealth in the most American way — homeownership.</p>

                    </div> <!-- end .promo-series__introduction -->
                            </div>
        
                    <div class="article-body__top-notes" data-pp-location="top-note">
                

        <div class="article-body__note article-body__note--co-publish">
                        <p>This article was produced for ProPublica’s Local Reporting Network in partnership with the <a href="https://vcij.org/">Virginia Center for Investigative Journalism at WHRO</a>. <a href="https://www.propublica.org/newsletters/dispatches">Sign up for Dispatches</a> to get stories like this one as soon as they are published.</p>

        </div>

    
            </div><!-- end .article-body__top-notes -->
        
        




                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="1.0">The city of Newport News, Virginia, and Christopher Newport University are creating a joint task force to reexamine the destruction of a Black neighborhood to make way for the school’s campus starting in the 1960s, and recommend possible redress for uprooted families.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="2.0">The new commission, announced Monday, will scrutinize four decades of the school’s property acquisitions, probing the decisions that led to locating and expanding its campus in the midst of a once-thriving Black community. It will also contact families displaced by Christopher Newport’s steady growth to ask what “restorative justice” would mean for them, and seek state assistance with potential relief for victims, according to a draft action plan.</p>
        
    
                        


   
            
